# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1944-negro-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The **1924 Colored World Series** was a best-of-nine match-up between the Negro National League champion Kansas City Monarchs and the Eastern Colored League champion Hilldale.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] In a ten-game series, the Monarchs narrowly defeated Hilldale 5 games to 4, with one tie game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] It was the first World Series between the respective champions of the NNL and ECL.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] It was the second year of existence for the ECL, but no agreement could be reached in 1923 for a postseason series, owing primarily to unresolved disputes between the leagues.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Five members of the Baseball Hall of Fame participated in the series: Biz Mackey, Judy Johnson, and Louis Santop played for Hilldale, while Bullet Rogan and José Méndez played for the Monarchs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Wilkinson was also inducted into the Hall.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Rogan pitched an 8-hitter, holding Hilldale scoreless until two out in the ninth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Warfield's bases-loaded error in the sixth allowed the Monarchs to score two, and aided by Cockrell's three errors in the same inning, opened up a five-run inning for the Monarchs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] , but instead used National League Park, home field of the Philadelphia Phillies, for the first two games, owing to its larger capacity.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Bill McCall could not get through the first inning, facing only three men and recording no outs before Bill "Plunk" Drake came in to relieve.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Hilldale led 9-0 by the end of the third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] shut out the normally high-scoring Monarchs on four singles.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The Monarchs took a one-run lead into the bottom of the ninth and again into the bottom of the twelfth, but were unable to put Hilldale away.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] William Bell pitched 12 innings for no decision; he played the thirteenth inning in right field, as Rogan came in from center field to pitch the thirteenth inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Monarch fielding errors in the fifth and ninth innings allowed Hilldale to stay in the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] received three intentional walks during the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The game was called on account of darkness after thirteen innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] , on account of Pennsylvania's blue laws, which did not allow professional baseball games on Sundays.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] After yesterday's tie game, another game was rescheduled for the following day.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Before a sparse weekday crowd, former Monarch Rube Currie relieved Red Ryan with one out in the third and the Monarchs leading 3–0, and shut them out the rest of the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Hilldale tied the game in the third on two base hits, a walk, and three steals, including Otto Briggs' steal of home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Two walks and two errors helped score Hilldale's winning run with none out in the ninth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] 's three-run inside-the-park home run with one out in the ninth shocked the crowd into silence and provided the difference in the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] A controversial umpire call and three defensive misplays helped set the table for Johnson's heroics.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Until the fatal ninth, the game had been a classic pitchers' duel between staff aces Winters and Rogan.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Winters finished the game with a flourish, retiring 25 of the last 26 men he faced.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Rube Foster had originally scheduled games Five, Six and Seven for his own ballpark, but Kansas City ownership and fans strenuously objected to losing such lucrative dates, and Foster relented.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Phil Cockrell started the game for Hilldale, but was driven from the mound in the first inning, allowing four runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] pitched the remainder of the game, but tired in the eighth when the Monarchs scored the tie-breaking run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Nip Winters pitched twelve innings and took the loss, while Méndez pitched brilliantly in relief for the win.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] stole home in the fourth inning to start the Monarchs' scoring.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Bullet Rogan did not hit the ball out of the infield, but still managed to get three hits, score one run, and drive in the winning tally in the twelfth inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] In one of Negro league baseball's legendary games, the Monarchs rallied for three runs in the ninth to stun Hilldale.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] foul popup, Duncan lined a single past Mackey that scored the tying and winning runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Also legendary was the vicious verbal assault that Warfield launched against Santop following the loss, laying blame for the loss squarely at Santop's feet.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Santop and others were already in tears in their locker room following the game, and it is one of Blackball's legends that Santop never recovered from the humiliation of Warfield's tirade.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Starting and completing his fourth game of the series, Nip Winters won for the third time to tie the series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] William Bell started for Kansas City, but was shelled with none out in the fifth inning when Hilldale tied the score 2-2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Drake pitched creditably until tiring in the ninth, when Hilldale scored two to win.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The Series was now tied for the third time.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] He matched Hilldale starter Scrip Lee zero for zero for seven full innings until Lee tired in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Lee changed from his normal submarine delivery to an overhand style in that inning, and the Monarchs scored five runs off of him, including one by Méndez himself.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] When Hilldale went out in the ninth, the Monarchs had won the first Colored World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The **1925 Colored World Series** was the second edition of the championship series in Negro league baseball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The series featured a rematch between the Hilldale Club of Darby, Pennsylvania, champion of the Eastern Colored League (ECL), and the Kansas City Monarchs, champion of the Negro National League (NNL) and winner of the previous year's match in the first Colored World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In 1925, Hilldale won the best-of-nine series, five games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] On the eve of the series, the Monarchs' star pitcher, Bullet Rogan, who had pitched a shutout in the deciding Game 7 of the NNL championship series, was injured while playing with his child at home, when a needle ran into his leg, leaving him unable to play in the World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City's manager and occasional pitcher was future Hall of Famer, 38-year-old José Méndez.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale featured three future Hall of Famers—catcher, Biz Mackey, third baseman, Judy Johnson, and 35-year-old backup catcher and pinch hitter, Louis Santop.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Attendance for series was disappointing—down more than 50 percent in comparison with the previous year's series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The financial results were so disappointing that one Kansas City Monarchs player said they would have been paid better barnstorming than playing in the series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] For both teams, the 1925 season would represent the end to a three-year run as league champions.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] (Both teams had won their league championships in 1923, when no world series was played.) Kansas City would eventually return to win additional championships, appearing in the 1942 and 1946 series and winning in 1942.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] For Hilldale, however, the 1925 championship would be its last, as the team folded in 1932.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In 1925, the NNL, which played in the Midwestern and Southern United States, held a split season championship, with 50 games scheduled for each half.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The teams qualifying to play in the league were the Kansas City Monarchs, the St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis Stars, the Memphis Red Sox, the Chicago American Giants, the Birmingham Black Barons, the Detroit Stars, the Indianapolis ABCs, and the Cuban Stars (West).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The first half opened on April 27 and closed on July 8, and the second half ran from July 11 through September 16.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The American Giants got off to an early lead in the NNL first half race, winning six of their first eight games.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The next week, Detroit pulled ahead, but by May 26 the Monarchs reached first place when they took three games of four from the visiting Detroit Stars.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The following week, the Monarchs took five straight from the American Giants, opening a lead on the other teams.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis Stars narrowed the lead but weren't able to catch the Monarchs, and on June 29 the Monarchs clinched the first-half title with a 2–1 victory over the Cuban Stars.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis Stars started the second half going 7–1, jumping to an early lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Soon the Chicago American Giants gained a slight lead, and during the first half of August the race between St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] When the American Giants dropped three games of four to the Monarchs from August 15–18 and then lost three straight to St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis on August 22–24, they dropped to third place and fell out of the race.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City were now in second place, and when they swept four games against St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis on September 5–8, they moved to within just .005 the Stars.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis held onto their lead, and finished the second half with a .760 winning percentage, .022 ahead of second place Kansas City.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The NNL scheduled a best-five-of-nine championship series, with the first three games in St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis on September 19–21 and the next three games (home games for the Monarchs) played in Chicago because the American Association's Kansas City Blues were finishing their season at home, tying up Muehlebach Field.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City won the first game 8–6, as Bullet Rogan pitched a complete game and Newt Allen, Dobie Moore, and Frank Duncan hit home runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis won the second game 6–3, behind the pitching of Roosevelt Davis and excellent plays in the field by Willie Wells, Cool Papa Bell, and Branch Russell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Rain prevented the third game from being played on September 21 or 22.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The league directors met and decided that the league championship series should be shortened to a best-of-seven series instead of best-of-nine.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis won the third game 3–2, behind a home run by Dewey Creacy, an RBI double by Bell, and another run scored by Bell on a wild throw by Moore.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City evened the series in game four, played in Chicago on September 26, beating St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis 5–4 with Bullet Rogan not only pitching, but also getting four hits, including a game-winning single in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Louis won 2–1, scoring both runs in the top of the ninth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] On September 28, the final two games were scheduled as a doubleheader, with Kansas City needing to win both games to avoid elimination.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The Monarchs won the first game 9–3 behind a strong pitching performance by William Bell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Rogan took the mound for the second game with only one day of rest and pitched a 4–0 shutout over the Stars, winning the league championship and the chance to face Hilldale in the World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The season opened on April 25 and finished on September 19.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale started the season with a 9–2 record, jumping to an early lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] By June 13, Harrisburg had taken a narrow lead and was scheduled to face Hilldale in a two-game series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale won the first game 11–9, retaking the lead, and the next day second game was called due to rain after Harrisburg had taken a 6–2 lead, prompting an outraged letter to the editor from Oscar Charleston, Harrisburg's manager and star center fielder.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Charleston complained about the quality of the umpiring in the first game and the decision to call the second game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Charleston's outburst prompted a strong rebuttal from Ed Bolden, owner of the Hilldale Club and chairman of the ECL commission.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Shortly after the game, Harrisburg retook the lead and held it for nearly a month.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] On July 19, Hilldale regained the lead when Baltimore swept a doubleheader from Harrisburg.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In mid-July, George Robinson, owner of the Wilmington Potomacs, announced that his team was folding; the league contracted to seven teams and the Potomacs players dispersed to other teams.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Over the next few weeks Hilldale widened its lead, and by early September they appeared to have the championship in hand.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With the Potomacs no longer playing and with many teams having missed games, teams in the league were unable to complete their 70-game schedules.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale easily won the ECL championship, finishing the season with a 45–13 record, while second-place Harrisburg finished 37–18.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The ECL commissioners and Rube Foster, president of the NNL, announced that the World Series would be a best-five-of-nine series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The first four games would be played in the home field of the NNL champion on October 1, 2, 3, and 4, with October 5 and 6 available for make-up games in case of rain.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Then the series would move to Philadelphia, the home for Hilldale, on October 8, 9, and 10.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] On Sunday, October 11, play would move to Jersey City, New Jersey because of blue laws in Philadelphia (though the leagues originally planned to play the game in New York City), and game nine (if necessary) would be played back in Philadelphia on October 12.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Because the parks had to be secured in advance, the teams agreed to play exhibition games on October 10 and 11 if the series ended early.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The games in Kansas City would take place at Muehlebach Field, the American Association ballpark, and the games in Philadelphia would take place at the Baker Bowl, the National League park, and the game in Jersey City would take place at the International League park.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale's regular lineup included Biz Mackey as the catcher, Tank Carr at first base, Frank Warfield, the manager, at second, Judy Johnson at third, Jake Stephens at shortstop, Clint Thomas in left field, George Johnson in center field, and Otto Briggs in right field.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Briggs was the leadoff hitter, while Warfield batted second in four of the six games, Carr batted third, Mackey was cleanup hitter, Judy Johnson hit fifth, Thomas sixth, and George Johnson seventh.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Their starting pitchers were Rube Currie, Phil Cockrell, Scrip Lee, and Nip Winters, with Red Ryan pitching in relief.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] From the bench, Louis Santop, Namon Washington, and Newt Robinson played as pinch hitters or defensive replacements.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City's roster took a major hit the day before the first game, when Bullet Rogan, their star pitcher, ran a needle into his leg while playing with his child on the floor.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] While attempting to remove it himself, he broke it, and had to have it removed surgically, leaving him unable to play in the series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Utility player Dink Mothell was confined to bed and also unable to play.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] During the World Series, Kansas City's regular lineup consisted of Frank Duncan at catcher, Lemuel Hawkins at first base, Newt Allen at second, Newt Joseph at third, Dobie Moore at shortstop, Wade Johnston in left field, Hurley McNair in center, and George Sweatt in right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Their most common batting order had Johnston leading off, Allen batting second, McNair third, Moore in the cleanup spot, Joseph fifth, Hawkins sixth, Sweatt seventh, and Duncan eighth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The starting pitchers were Cliff Bell, William Bell, Nelson Dean, and Bill Drake, with manager José Méndez pitching in relief.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The only Monarchs bench player to appear in the series was pinch hitter Hooks Foreman.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale won the series opener in Kansas City, 5–2, in 12 innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The winning pitcher was Rube Currie, who struck out six and gave up nine hits, two runs, and one walk in a 12-inning complete game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Bill Drake, who pitched the last two innings for Kansas City in relief for starter Cliff Bell, was charged with the loss.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Otto Briggs drove in the go-ahead run with a single in the top of the 12th.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The game was scoreless until the bottom of the fourth inning, when McNair led off with a single to left, then scored on Moore's double to right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the seventh, Hilldale evened the score.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Thomas drew a walk to lead off the inning, and with the infield drawn in looking for a bunt, George Johnson drilled a single into center, advancing Thomas to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The next batter, Warfield, hit the first pitch for a long fly to right field, and Thomas scored after the catch.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The game remained tied 1–1 through the ninth inning, so it went to extra innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the 11th, Briggs led off with a line drive single up the middle, which Cliff Bell attempted to catch, hurting his hand.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] After Bell walked Stephens, Kansas City brought in Drake as a relief pitcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The next batter, Carr, singled to left-center and Briggs attempted to score from second, but was out on George Johnson's throw to the plate.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] According to *The Chicago Defender*, "in tagging Briggs, he [Duncan] pulled him two feet off and away from the plate for an out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] It was indeed a great play as well as a great peg by Johnston." However, the next batter, Mackey, singled to center and scored Stephens from second, giving Hilldale the lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, McNair reached with one out on an infield single.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] He then stole second, and Moore tripled to right, scoring McNair.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] But when the next batter, Joseph, hit a ground ball to third, Judy Johnson was able to bluff Moore back to third before throwing Joseph out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hawkins then grounded out to short, ending the inning with a 2–2 tie.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the 12th, Drake hit the first batter he faced, George Johnson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Warfield singled to right, advancing Johnson to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] After Currie struck out, Briggs singled to left, scoring Johnson, and advanced to second on the throw to the plate.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] After Stephens struck out, Carr singled and drove in McNair and Warfield.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Mackey then struck out to retire the side, but Hilldale was ahead 5–2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, Sweatt grounded out to the pitcher, Duncan flew out to left, and Foreman, pinch hitting for Drake, grounded out to second, ending the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the second game, the Monarchs evened the series with a 5–3 victory.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Nelson Dean was the winning pitcher as he struck out two and gave up eight hits, three runs, and four walks in 8+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The losing pitcher, Phil Cockrell, was hurt by a couple of costly errors, as he struck out four and gave up 10 hits and four walks in a complete game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the eighth, Kansas City broke open a 2–2 tie when an error by Jake Stephens was followed by RBI singles by Lemuel Hawkins and Frank Duncan.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Hilldale answered with one run, but was unable to catch the Monarchs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City got the first run on the board in the first inning, when McNair knocked a one-out double over Thomas's head in left field and Allen drove him in with a single to right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of second, Hilldale responded with two runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Mackey led off with a walk and Judy Johnson bunted him to second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Thomas then singled to left center, driving home Mackey.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] George Johnson hit a single to center, and Thomas advanced to third and Johnson to second when McNair fumbled the ball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale then put on a squeeze play to score Thomas, with Warfield out at first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale held onto their 2–1 lead until the seventh inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the fourth, they threatened when Judy Johnson led off with a single and stole second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With two outs, Warfield hit a line drive headed for right field, but Hawkins made a leaping catch.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the seventh, Sweatt led off for Kansas City with a single to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Duncan sacrificed, then Dean doubled to right to score Sweatt, tying the game at two runs apiece.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the eighth inning, Allen led off with an infield hit.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Moore struck out, but Joseph reached when Hilldale shortstop Stephens fumbled a ground ball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hawkins then singled to center, scoring Allen.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Next, Sweatt walked, loading the bases, and Duncan hit a bounder to third that Judy Johnson had to leap to catch, allowing Joseph to score an unearned run and Duncan to reach first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Dean then hit a fly ball that Stephens caught on the edge of the grass, but he let Hawkins score from third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] *The Chicago Defender* wrote, "The crowd was puzzled, because it looked like Stephens had plenty of time to set himself to throw.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] It looked to the scorers as if he hadn't figured wheretu Hawkins would take a chance to score after the catch.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] When he did wake up he threw wide to Mackey." The Monarchs now led 5–2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Warfield led off with a walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Cockrell grounded into a force play by Moore at second, then Briggs singled to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Santop, pinch hitting, made the second out on a fly to right center, then Carr singled to right to score Cockrell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] An intentional walk was issued to Mackey, and Judy Johnson ended the game with a fly out to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale won the third game, 3–1, in ten innings, taking a series lead of two games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Red Ryan, who pitched two scoreless innings in relief of Hilldale starter Scrip Lee, was credited with the win, and Monarchs manager and pitcher José Méndez, who gave up all three runs in a three-inning relief outing for starter William Bell, was charged with the loss.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The game was scoreless until the bottom of the eighth, when Kansas City scored a run, which was matched by Hilldale in the top of the ninth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale's decisive runs in the top of the tenth—an RBI double by Namon Washington, followed by an RBI single by Newt Robinson—were provided by late inning substitutes.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Although no runs were scored in the first seven innings, Hilldale mounted several threats.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the second inning, they left runners at second and third after a walk by Thomas and a double by Stephens.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the third, Briggs led off with an infield single and was sacrificed to second, but was then picked off by Bell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the fourth, Mackey led off with a single, and Judy Johnson followed with a double.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Thomas then grounded to short, and Moore threw out Mackey at the plate.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] After Thomas stole second, George Johnson lined out to first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Stephens walked to load the bases, but Lee struck out to end the threat.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the eighth, Carr led off with a walk, Mackey got an infield hit, and Judy Johnson singled to short left to load the bases with no outs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Thomas grounded to short, and Moore threw out Carr at home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Santop pinch hit for George Johnson; according to *The Chicago Defender*: "'Big Bertha' hit one to Moore that was hotter than tabasco sauce.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Meanwhile, Lee held the Monarchs hitless through the first four innings, and to one hit through seven.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With two outs in the bottom of the eighth, the Monarchs offense finally came alive, when Johnston singled to right, and McNair reached on an error by Carr.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Allen then singled to right, driving in Johnston to take a 1–0 lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale responded in the top of the ninth, when Cockrell, pinch hitting for Lee, reached base with a one-out walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Briggs followed with a single to left, and Warfield grounded to shortstop, forcing Briggs at second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With two outs, Carr singled to right, scoring Cockrell and tying the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Hilldale reliever Ryan retired the side in order.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the tenth, Judy Johnson led off with a single to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Thomas sacrificed him to second, then Washington doubled to center to drive in the go-ahead run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Robinson singled to right, scoring Washington, and took second on the throw to the plate, but was thrown out trying to take third as well.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the tenth, Duncan hit a one-out double to left, but Foreman and Johnston both flied out to end the game, with a 3–1 victory for Hilldale.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale won the fourth game, 7–3, in front of the largest crowd of the series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The winning pitcher was Nip Winters, who pitched a complete game, allowing eight hits and three runs, striking out eight, and walking three.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The loser, Bill Drake, also pitched a complete game and yielded 11 hits and seven runs, struck out three, and walked three.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] A high wind caused both teams trouble with judging fly balls.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale took a 2–1 lead in the fourth when Biz Mackey tripled and Judy Johnson drove him in with a sacrifice fly.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] They added a run in the fifth, and Kansas City answered in the seventh, narrowing the margin to 3–2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Hilldale broke the game open with four runs in the top of the ninth, and the Monarchs only managed one run in the bottom of the ninth as they fell behind in the series, three games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the first, Warfield singled with one out on a hit that Allen was just able to knock down.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Carr then singled to center, with the wind causing an unusual hop that enabled Warfield to race home with the first run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the second, Kansas City answered, with Joseph hitting a one-out triple to right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hawkins then grounded to Warfield, who threw home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Joseph slid into home spikes first, and Mackey dropped the ball, allowing the run to score and tying the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the fourth, Mackey hit a one-out triple to right field.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Judy Johnson followed with a long fly out to right, scoring Mackey and giving Hilldale a 2–1 lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With two outs, Stephens grounded to short and beat out Moore's throw.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] He then stole second and advanced to third on a passed ball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Briggs singled to right, scoring Stephens.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the seventh, Sweatt led off with a hit to right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] After Duncan struck out, Drake hit a fly ball to center, which the wind caused George Johnson to misjudge; when it rolled away, Drake reached third with a triple, driving in Sweatt, and narrowing Hilldale's lead to 3–2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the ninth, George Johnson led off with a triple to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Winters drove him in with a single to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Stephens grounded to third, forcing Winters at second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Briggs followed with a double to right, advancing Stephens to third, and Warfield tripled to right-center, driving in two more runs, and scored himself when Joseph missed McNair's throw to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City entered the bottom of the ninth trailing 7–2, and Joseph led off with a single to right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hawkins beat out an infield hit to Judy Johnson at third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Sweatt singled to right, scoring Joseph and advancing Hawkins to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The next three Kansas City batters, however, made easy outs, ending the game 7–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The series resumed in Philadelphia, where Hilldale won their first home game, 2–1, taking a series lead of four games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The winning pitcher was Rube Currie, who gave up six hits and one run, striking out four and walking one in a complete game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The losing pitcher, Cliff Bell, lasted 4+2⁄3 innings and gave up eight hits and two runs, striking out one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Both of Hilldale's runs came in the fourth inning, when Tank Carr hit a one-out solo home run, which was followed by a pair of doubles by Biz Mackey and Clint Thomas.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Moore led off the top of the second inning with a hit off Currie's glove, but he was caught off first by catcher Mackey and thrown out trying to advance to second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the fourth, McNair led off with a single to right, and a one-out single by Joseph advanced him to second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Again, the Monarchs lost their opportunity to a baserunning blunder, when McNair was caught trying to steal third with two outs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the fourth, Hilldale took the lead with Carr's one-out solo home run over the high right field wall.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Mackey followed with a double hit against the same wall.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With two outs, Thomas hit a ground ball past Moore for a double, scoring Mackey, and giving Hilldale a 2–0 lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the fifth, they threatened again with Stephens and Currie hitting a pair of singles to lead off the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Briggs then hit into a double play, and with Dean brought in to relieve Cliff Bell, Hilldale tried a squeeze play, but Warfield was thrown out on the bunt.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the sixth, Allen hit a one-out double to the fence in center field.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] With two outs, Moore doubled to right, driving in Allen and narrowing Hilldale's lead to one run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the sixth, Hilldale had runners on first and third with one out, and Thomas hit a fly caught by Allen in short right near the foul line.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Carr tried to score from third, and was gunned down on the relay from Allen to Hawkins to Duncan.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Kansas City's only hit in the last three innings was a one-out double by Duncan in the top of the seventh, so they were unable to catch Hilldale.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] On October 9, heavy rain forced the sixth game to be delayed a day.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] On Saturday, October 10, play resumed despite freezing temperatures and gusting winds that kept all but the hardiest of fans away.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Phil Cockrell, a spitball pitcher, was the winner, as he allowed eight hits and two runs, striking out six, and walking four, in a complete game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] William Bell, the loser, also went the distance, as he allowed nine hits and five runs, struck out four, and walked one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Hilldale scored runs in the fourth and fifth innings and two in the sixth, then Biz Mackey hit a solo home run to lead off the seventh.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The Monarchs answered with one run each in the seventh and ninth innings, but fell to Hilldale, 5–2, ending the series with Hilldale victorious five games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The Hilldale Club was first to score in the bottom of the fourth, when Thomas hit a two-out double to center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] George Johnson drove him in with a single to left.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the fifth, Warfield reached base with one out on an error by Moore.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Carr walked, and Mackey doubled off the right field wall, driving in Warfield.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Judy Johnson grounded to Bell, and Carr was thrown out trying to get back to third after attempting to score on the play.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Thomas flied out to end the inning, and Hilldale was up, 2–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the sixth, Cockrell reached with one out on an error by Joseph.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Briggs grounded out to Allen, advancing Stephens to third, and then Stephens scored when Warfield beat out a hit to Joseph at third, widening Hilldale's lead to 4–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the top of the seventh, Allen led off with a single to right.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] McNair sacrificed, and after Moore flied out, Allen stole third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Joseph was hit by a pitch, and Hawkins beat out a slow roller to Judy Johnson at third, scoring Allen, and making the score, 4–1.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the seventh, Mackey led off with a home run over the right field fence, making it 5–1.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The Monarchs' final opportunity came in the top of the ninth, when McNair led off the inning with a double off the scoreboard.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Moore followed with a double off the right field wall, scoring McNair.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Joseph reached base safely on an error by Judy Johnson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] But when Hawkins hit a short fly to left, Thomas raced in to catch it.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Stephens fumbled a ground ball hit by Duncan, loading the bases with one out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Foreman pinch hit for Sweatt, but struck out, and George Johnson sprinted in to catch William Bell's fly for the last out, ending the game, 5–2, and the series, five games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Because the ballpark in Jersey City had already been retained, the two teams played an exhibition on game in Jersey City on Sunday, October 11.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The Monarchs' young pitcher, Chet Brewer, held the champions to one run, as Kansas City beat Hilldale, 6–1.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] The Hilldale players made seven errors, and the Hilldale starter, Nip Winters, gave up five walks.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Although the game did not count in the series, it was counted in the financial results of the series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Total attendance for the series (including the exhibition game) was 20,067, less than half the 45,857 who had attended the ten games of the 1924 series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Total receipts were $21,045, in comparison with $52,113 the previous year.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Total expenses were $15,173, including $3,748 for park rent, $5,543 for railroad fares and hotels for the two ball clubs, $2,050 for war tax, and $827 for umpires.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] A surplus of $5,872 was available for distribution, with $1,233 going to the owners of the victorious Hilldale club, the same amount split among their players, and $822 each going to the owner and the players of the Kansas City Monarchs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1925-colored-world-series] Newspaper reports described the financial results as disappointing and attributed the poor attendance to cold weather and a shortened and lopsided series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The **1926 Colored World Series** was the championship tournament for the 1926 season of Negro league baseball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] It matched the Chicago American Giants, champions of the Negro National League (1920–1931), and the Bacharach Giants of Atlantic City, New Jersey, champions of the Eastern Colored League.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Initially planned as a best-of-nine series, two ties meant that the series went eleven games.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago won just once in the first six games, but games 1 and 4 had ended in ties, meaning that they only trailed three games to one when the Series shifted to Chicago.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] They were down to their final game after losing the eighth game, but the Chicago American Giants proceeded to win the next three games to complete the comeback and win their first ever World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Claude "Red" Grier of the Bacharach Giants pitched a no-hitter in Game 3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] No pitcher would throw a no-hitter in a postseason game in the major leagues until Don Larsen did so thirty years later.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] This was the second postseason for the Negro leagues to involve a Championship Series played prior to the World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Giants lost four of the first five games (with Game 4 being the only win).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, the Giants proceeded to win four consecutive games at home, however, to clinch the pennant, which included three games decided by one run and a Game 9 that ended in the fifth inning with a 5–0 win.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] It was their fourth league title, all done in the span of six years.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] John Henry Lloyd, who had managed the Atlantic City Bacharach Giants in 1925, left the team and signed as manager with the Lincoln Giants after the Bacharach Giants attempted to reduce his salary.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Bacharach Giants' shortstop, Dick Lundy, was promoted to player-manager in his place, returning to the post he had held in 1923 before Lloyd's arrival.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] At the winter meetings, the Eastern Colored League admitted the Newark Stars (also known as the Newark ABC's) to the league as the eighth team.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The seven teams that had finished the previous season were the Bacharach Giants of Atlantic City, the Baltimore Black Sox, the Brooklyn Royal Giants, the Cuban Stars (East), the Harrisburg Giants, the Hilldale Club, and the Lincoln Giants of New York.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The two leagues also announced a $3,000 maximum monthly salary limit for each team.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The league, then in its fourth year, was attempting to play a 70-game full-season competition, but had experienced problems in enforcing a uniform schedule.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The league decided that a team if a team failed to play at least 50 league games, it would not be eligible to compete in the Colored World Series, or to have claim to the money awarded to the second or third place clubs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Early in the season, the Bacharach Giants trailed in the race.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] On May 23, their record was 2–7, placing them in seventh place, trailing the league-leading Harrisburg Giants.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] By June 28, their record had improved to 9–12 and they had inched into sixth place, ahead of the Brooklyn Royal Giants and the last place Newark Stars.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Cuban Stars were in first place with a 10–3 record.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A week later, the manager of the Newark Stars announced that they would quit the league and disband, leaving the league with seven teams.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] And although the Brooklyn Royal Giants remained in the league, they were rumored to be planning to leave the league the next season as they had only played six games and were disregarding the league schedule.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Instead of playing league games, they were playing semi-pro teams in Brooklyn or barnstorming in upstate New York.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the month of July, the Bacharach Giants took off, winning 13 straight games, before losing to the Cuban Stars on July 26.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] During August, the Cuban Stars clung to their lead in the pennant race, with the Bacharach Giants, the Harrisburg Giants, the Hilldale Club, and the Lincoln Giants all remaining in the mix.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] But by August 31, the Bacharach Giants had moved into first place with a 31–20 record.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A week later, the Bacharach Giants were solidly in first place with a 33–20 (.623) record and four games remaining before the scheduled September 15 end of the season.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The second-place Harrisburg Giants had a 25–17 (.595) record, and the third-place Hilldale Club had a 34–24 (.586) record.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Over the winter, Rube Foster, the co-owner and manager of the American Giants (as well as president of the Negro National League), engaged in a series of trades and transactions designed to overhaul and rebuild his aging team.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He traded for Rube Curry, who had pitched for the victors of 1925 Negro World Series—the Hilldale Club.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He traded for outfielder George Sweatt from Kansas City, pitcher Robert Poindexter and outfielder Sandy Thompson from the Birmingham Black Barons, sending away long-time American Giants players Cristóbal Torriente, Juan Padrón, and Bingo DeMoss (who went to manage the Indianapolis ABCs).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] From the Memphis Red Sox, which had forfeited its NNL franchise, he picked up Sanford Jackson, Charlie Williams, and catcher Pythias Russ.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Third baseman Dave Malarcher was named as captain of the team.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Memphis and the Birmingham teams, which had played in the NNL in 1925, left to join the new Negro Southern League and did not renew their franchises, which were returned to the league.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Their players were distributed to other teams.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A new franchise was approved for the Cleveland Elites, owned by Sam Shepard of St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Louis; Candy Jim Taylor was named as the team's manager.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The league would have eight teams—the Chicago American Giants, Cleveland Elites, Cuban Stars (West), Dayton Marcos, Detroit Stars, Indianapolis ABCs, Kansas City Monarchs, and St.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bullet Rogan took over as player-manager of the Monarchs, and Arvell "Bill" Riggins became the player-manager of the Detroit Stars.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The schedule called for the season to open on May 1, with the league playing two halves and the winners of each half playing a league championship series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The defending champion Monarchs jumped to an early lead in the race, winning all of their first nine games of the season and 13 of their first 15, with the American Giants in second place winning 10 of their first 13.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] On May 18, however, the Monarchs suffered a tragic setback when their star shortstop, Dobie Moore, was shot in the leg by a girlfriend, resulting in compound fractures that would end his professional baseball career.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The American Giants immediately retook the lead in the race, with Kansas City dropping to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] But the Monarchs quickly rebounded and regained the lead, winning two consecutive series, eight of nine games, against the American Giants.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The first half race finished on July 5 with Kansas City winning it with a 35–12 record.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Detroit (34–17) was in second place and Chicago (28–16) in third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Two weeks into the second half, the league's weakest team, the Dayton Marcos, withdrew from the league and folded.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A week later the Cleveland Elites also quit.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Cuban Stars had initially announced that they would return early to Cuba, but when Cleveland withdrew the Stars decided to stay and allow the league to continue with six teams.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Meanwhile, the American Giants jumped to an early lead in the second half race by going 22–1 in their first 23 games.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In late August, American Giants manager Rube Foster experienced a nervous breakdown after several weeks of exhibiting erratic behavior.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He was taken into custody at his home by police and, after several days of observation, was committed to the mental asylum at Kankakee State Hospital.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Dave Malarcher took over the management of the team.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With a 29–7 record, the American Giants won the second half, narrowly edging the second-place Monarchs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The NNL League Championship Series was a best-five-of-nine contest played from September 18 to 29.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The series opened in Kansas City, where the Monarchs won the first three games, 4–3, 6–5, and 5–0, before the American Giants won the fourth game 4–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Traveling to Chicago to play the remainder of the series, the Monarchs won the fifth game 11–5, leaving them ahead four games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Chicago Giants, however, rallied to win the next two games by scores of 2–0 (a shutout by Curry) and 4–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] On September 29 the Monarchs were still leading four games to three with a doubleheader scheduled.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] If the American Giants won, the teams would play a second, five-inning game and the winner would board the train to Atlantic City for the World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The teams' ace pitchers, Foster and Rogan, faced off in a great pitching duel.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Both were pitching shutouts as the game went to the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Jackson beat out a roller to third, Foster sacrificed him to second, and with two outs, Thompson singled to drive in the winning run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] When Rogan (the Monarchs' manager) saw that Foster was warming up to start the second game also, he decided to go back himself, taking the ball from Chet Brewer who had been scheduled to start.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The decisions worked out better for the American Giants as Foster pitched his second shutout in one day.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago beat Kansas City 5–0, thereby clinching the league championship and a berth in the World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] As late as the beginning of September, *Chicago Defender* sportswriter Fay Young wrote that "there might not be any world series this year" because the Cuban Stars (East) were narrowly leading the Eastern Colored League pennant race.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] There were concerns that the Cuban squad did not have a park and would not generate enough attendance to cover the expenses of a series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] By mid-September the leagues had agreed to a best-five-of-nine-game series, with the first four games to be held in the East with games split among Atlantic City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore, and the last five games played in the West.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Atlantic City's regular lineup consisted of Willie Jones as catcher, Chance Cummings as first baseman, Chano García as second baseman, Oliver Marcelle as third baseman, Dick Lundy as shortstop and manager, Ambrose Reid in left field, Chaney White in center field, and Luther Farrell in right field.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Their starting pitchers were Rats Henderson, Claude Grier, Alonzo Mitchell, and Hubert Lockhart, and Roy Roberts was a relief pitcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Their bench included outfielder Elias "Country" Brown and backup catcher Joe Lewis.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The pitching staff included starting pitchers Willie Foster, Rube Curry, Willie Powell, George Harney, and Webster McDonald, and relief pitcher Sam Crawford.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The series opener in Atlantic City ended in a 3–3 tie when it was called after nine innings due to darkness.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Curry started for the American Giants and pitched into the eighth inning, when he was lifted for Foster.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Henderson went the distance for the Bacharach Giants.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the top of the second, Jackson came to bat with the bases loaded and no outs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He reached base on a fielder's choice hit to the pitcher; Henderson's throw home was high and wide allowing Hines to score with Chicago taking a 1–0 lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Bacharach Giants avoided further damage when Henderson struck out Curry and Sweatt was thrown out trying to score on a passed ball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Bacharach Giants took the lead in the bottom of the fourth, when White, Lundy, and Farrell hit consecutive singles with two outs, driving in two runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the top of the sixth, the American Giants regained the lead when Jackson batted again with the bases loaded, this time with two outs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He singled to right, driving in Sweatt and Malarcher and giving Chicago a 3–2 lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the seventh, the home team evened the score when Farrell hit a one-out home run over the right field fence.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the eighth, the Bacharach Giants threatened again, loading the bases with two outs for Farrell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Foster, who just two days earlier had pitched two shutouts in a doubleheader to clinch the championship, came in to relieve Curry and struck out Farrell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Neither team scored in the ninth, and the game was called on account of darkness.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The original schedule called for an off day on Saturday, October 2, but due to the tie in the first game, a second game in Atlantic City was hastily arranged.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The American Giants took an early lead that the Bacharach Giants were unable to overcome, as Chicago won 7–6.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Harney of the American Giants was the winning pitcher, while Grier took the loss for the Bacharach Giants.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Bacharach Giants took a 1–0 lead in the bottom of the first on a sacrifice fly by Marcell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the top of the second, though, the American Giants broke the game open.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] After five singles, a walk, and a hit batter, the American Giants had taken a 4–1 lead and had the bases loaded with two outs when Hines came to bat for the second time in the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Grier fell behind Hines with a 3–0 count, and Lundy brought in Lockhart to relieve and try to get the home team out of the jam.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Hines then hit a triple to deep left field, driving in three and putting the American Giants ahead 7–1.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Bacharach Giants chipped away at the American Giants lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the third, Malarcher hit a double to right-center that drove in two, making the score 7–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the sixth, the Bacharach Giants loaded the bases with one out after a single, a walk, and a hit batter.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] García singled to center, driving in two runs and knocking Harney out of the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] McDonald was brought in to relieve him, but he walked Lockhart to load the bases again.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Reid then singled off the short fence in right field driving in another run, but the right fielder Gardner quickly fielded the ball and fired it home, so García retreated to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The catcher Hines then noticed that Lockhart had rounded second, so he fired the ball to the shortstop, Jackson, picking off Lockhart.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Meanwhile, García broke for home but was thrown out at the plate.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] During the play, García collided with Hines and the impact knocked him out for several minutes, but he was able to return to the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The inning was over, and the American Giants still led 7–6.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago held on to the lead and that was the final score.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] On October 3, the Bacharach Giants beat the American Giants 10–0, as Claude Grier made baseball history by pitching the first no-hitter in a Colored World Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Grier accomplished this feat the day after he had started and lost Game 2, knocked out in the second inning and giving up seven runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] While holding the American Giants hitless and striking out eight, Grier walked six batters and two American Giants reached base on errors.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Crawford pitched a scoreless eighth inning for the American Giants.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The Atlantic City victory evened the Series at one game apiece.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The weather was unusually hot, and attendance was disappointing for a Sunday game in the larger city.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the first, Reid led off for the Bacharach Giants reaching base and advancing to second on a throwing error by Jackson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Cummings singled to right, then Marcell bunted to a single, scoring Reid.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] White also tried bunting and reached base and advanced to second on a throwing error by Malarcher, with Cumming scoring.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Lundy followed with a single to right scoring Marcell and White, and the home team was ahead 4–0 before having made an out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The American Giants threatened a rally in the top of the fifth when Malarcher led off with a walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With two outs, McDonald reached base on a sharply hit ball to first that got past Cummings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The scoring official ruled it an error, though some fans said it should have been recorded as a hit, which would have ended Grier's no-hit bid.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] This was followed by a walk issued to Gardner, loading the bases.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] But Thompson hit a come-backer to the pitcher and was thrown out, ending the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the sixth, the Bacharach Giants scored six more runs to break the game open.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] García, leading off the inning, was hit by a pitch, and Grier doubled to left.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Then Cummings singled to center, driving in Grier, and Sweatt misplayed the ball allowing Reid to score and Cummings to advance to second on the error.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Marcell singled, advancing Cummings to third, and White hit a sacrifice fly to score him.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Lundy grounded into a fielder's choice to shortstop for the second out, and Farrell followed with a single advancing Lundy to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Farrell and Lundy then attempted a double steal.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The throw arrived to the catcher in time to tag out Lundy, but Hines dropped the ball and Lundy scored on another error (the fourth by the American Giants).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Then Jones doubled, driving in Farrell to make it 10–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The fourth game ended in a 4–4 tie when the game was called due to darkness after nine innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] It was played in Philadelphia under unseasonably hot weather.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Henderson started for Atlantic City and Foster for Chicago, and both starting pitchers threw complete games.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The American Giants scored twice in the top of the first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Gardner led off with a single to left, followed by a single to right by Malrcher that advanced Gardner to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] After a sacrifice bunt advanced Malarcher to second, Hines hit a fly to left that scored Gardner, while Malarcher advanced to third on the throw to the plate.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Sweatt then hit a two-out single to right scoring Malarcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] They added another run in the fourth when Sweatt hit a one-out double to right-center.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With two outs, Jackson doubled down the right field line driving in Sweatt and making it 3–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom of the fifth the Bacharach Giants scored four to take the lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] García led off with a walk, then with two outs Cummings singled.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Marcell grounded to shortstop, but Jackson made a wild throw to first base, allowing García to score and the runners to advance to second and third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] White singled to right, driving in both runners to tie the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Lundy followed him with a triple to deep center scoring White and putting the Bacharach Giants ahead 4–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the sixth inning, the Bacharach Giants threatened to add on when García led off with a triple for the Bacharach Giants.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Henderson flied out to right, and García attempted to score but was thrown out at the plate by Gardner, so the score remained 4–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The American Giants evened the score in the seventh.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The first two batters, Jackson and Williams, both hit bunt singles.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Foster hit a sacrifice bunt to advance the runners.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With two outs, Jackson attempted to steal home and scored when Henderson's pitch got past the catcher, which was ruled as a passed ball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] When the ninth inning ended with the score still tied, the game was called because of darkness.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago American would blow a lead for the third time in five games, and this time it would cost them a win.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] They began the game with a lead on a series of unearned runs in the first inning that meant three runs on zero hits and three errors committed by Bacharach.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Jelly Gardner started the game with a walk by pitcher Alonzo Mitchell, and a passed ball by catcher Willie Jones meant he went to second base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The next batter in Dave Malarcher would advance to first base on an error by first baseman Chance Cummings that gave Gardner enough time to score form second.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A sacrifice bunt and an error led to runners on the corner, and a sacrifice groundout by George Sweatt scored Malarcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] An error by shortstop Dick Lundy on the next batter would score John Hines from second base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The game would stay that way until the fifth inning, when Bacharach made their charge, doing so on the strength of seven hits and two errors.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Starting the proceedings was Jones, who started the inning with a single off Chicago starter Rube Curry.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] After a flyout, pitcher Alonzo Mitchell scored the first run on his second hit of the game (he would go 3-for-4) on a triple.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Ambrose Reid would hit a single to center field that would score Mitchell, and Chance Cummings followed him with a single, with an error by Curry leading to runners on second and third base with one out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Oliver Marcell broke the game open with a hit to right field that scored Reid, and an error committed by catcher John Hines led to Cummings scoring to make it 4-3 and Marcell made it to third base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago inched closer in the subsequent inning, starting with a hit by Malarcher and a walk to Sandy Thompson, and they went to third and second base on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A subsequent strikeout meant two outs for Jim Brown, but he would line a triple to right field to score two runs and narrow the deficit to 6–5.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, Sanford Jackson grounded out to the first baseman to end the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach closed the scoring in the seventh inning after Chaney White had started the inning with a walk and stole second base before a two-out double by Jones drove White home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago managed to get a runner on first base in the final inning on a hit by Jackson, but two force-outs closed the game out as Alonzo Mitchell finalized a 2–1 series lead for Bacharach.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He pitched a complete game while allowing four hits and five runs (two earned) with three strikeouts and walks.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach withstood a brief rally by Chicago to close the New Jersey end of the Series with a win to go up three games to one (with two ties) in the Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach started the scoring in the first inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A leadoff single by Ambrose Reid was followed by two outs but him on second base and Dick Lundy scored him hin with a double to the outfield to make it 1–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the next inning, Chano García lined a two-out walk, and a walk to Claude Grier was followed by a single by Reid to make it 2–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago would get their chance to even it up in the fourth inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Dave Malarcher hit a leadoff bunt for a single, and Sandy Thompson also lined a bunt successfully for a hit (the next batter would try to bunt as well, but he only succeeded in advancing the runners).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] George Sweatt lined a single to left to score two runs and tie the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A bunt led to an error and two men on with one out, but two straight outs led to the game still tied after four.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach broke the tie with a run in each of the next four innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the fifth, Reid had a triple to leadoff the inning and Oliver Marcell bunted him home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the sixth, Reid had a two-run single to score Alonzo Mitchell from second base after he had a single earlier.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the seventh, Marcell had a leadoff double and Lundy would score him after his sharp grounder to the third baseman resulted in an error.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago had a leadoff double by Powell and a walk by Gardner, and Hines scored Powell and Gardner on a two-out single to make it 5–4.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach followed with a leadoff single by García that was eventually scored in by Chance Cummings on a double.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago had a leadoff walk, but the 7-8-9 hitters all hit outs to close out the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Willie Powell pitched eight innings while allowing six runs (five earned) on twelve hits with two walks and two strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Claude Grier allowed four runs on six hits and three walks.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago blew a lead for the fourth and final time in the Series, but a late rally gave them a win to make the series 3–2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach started the scoring in the third after two ground outs led to Ambrose Reid at bat.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He hit a double to right field, and Chance Cummings scored him in with a single to right to make it 1–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago followed in the fourth inning after having loaded the bases on a single, an error, and a hit by pitch.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Charlie Williams would help score a run when starting pitcher Hubert Lockhart threw a walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chances for more were dashed when the runner on third was picked off, but the game was tied.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] On their next chance to bat in the fifth, they broke the game open.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With one out, Jelly Gardner lined a single that was followed by a walk to Dave Malarcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Sandy Thompson would line a double into left field that scored Gardner.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] One batter later, George Sweatt hit a triple to center that cleared the bases and gave them a 4–1 lead.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach would chip away at the lead late in the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the seventh inning, Willie Jones hit a leadoff double to right field.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] One batter later, Hubert Lockhart hit a single to left to score Jones and make it 4–2.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the eighth inning, Oliver Marcell hit a leadoff single to right field, and Chaney White followed it with a triple to left to cut the game to 4–3.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A sacrifice fly by Joe Lewis score White to make it 4-4.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The game was decided in the ninth inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Starter Hubert Lockhart had gotten the leadoff hitter to pop-out, but he was replaced after Dave Malarcher had hit a single and stole second base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Lockhart had allowed nine hits in 8+1⁄3 innings with four walks and one strikeout.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Henderson got Sandy Thompson to strikeout to make it two outs with a runner on second for John Hines.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, a passed ball by catcher Willie Jones advanced Malarcher to third base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Hines responded with a single to right field that scored the winning run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bill Foster had allowed four runs on eight hits with three walks and five strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach inched one closer to winning the Series with a shutout win over the Giants that included a complete-game shutout by Rats Henderson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] By the time of the eighth inning, Bacharach had left six runners on base combined, while Chicago had left three behind.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Country Brown started the eighth inning with a single through second base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chance Cummings followed that up by advancing to first base on an error by first baseman Jim Brown.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] A wild pitch by starting pitcher George Harney meant that there was runners on third and second base, and Oliver Marcell was soon intentionally walked.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With Chaney White at the plate, he belted a single to left field that left fielder Sandy Thompson would have trouble fielding after it landed, and the result was that White cleared the bases and advanced to second base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The scoring subsided afterwards on two groundouts and a flyout, but Bacharach led 3–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The two teams each had a chance in the ninth for further scoring.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach had the bases loaded with two out on the basis of a single and two walks, but a strikeout ended the threat.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago responded with a leadoff walk by Jelly Gardner, but a pop-out and a force-out meant that Sandy Thompson was at first base with two out, although a single by John Hines put the tying run at the plate in George Sweatt.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, he flied out to right field to end the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Henderson threw a complete-game shutout while allowing just three hits while striking out seven and walking two.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Harney allowed three runs (one earned) on six hits while walking six and striking out two.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago mustered runs early and withstood a potential rally to stay alive in the Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago started the second inning by getting on bases by walks to John Hines and George Sweatt.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Hines was picked off second, and a ground out meant there was two outs with one on first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, Sanford Jackson would line a triple to left field to score Sweatt, and Charlie Williams responded with a single to make it 2–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the fourth, a two-out double by Jim Brown was rewarded after Jackson hit a single to make it 3–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the sixth, walks to Hines and Sweatt led to a RBI single by Brown.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Jackson would drive in a run on a fielder's choice, while a passed ball by the catcher led to another run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach had their only scoring in the eighth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Dick Lundy singled to leadoff the inning, and Luther Farrell followed with a single.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Willie Jones had a double to make it 6–1, while Chano García made it 6–3 on a single (with an error by the catcher); a double play got García out at home to end the scoring.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the ninth, they garnered a single but no further hitting to end the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Claude Grier threw eight innings while allowing six runs (four earned) on seven hits, six walks, and nine strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Rube Curry threw a complete game while allowing three runs on eight hits and having seven strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago continued their chance to stay alive in the Series with an onslaught of timely hitting to rout Bacharach.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Ten batters went to bat in the fourth inning, and seven scored on seven hits and one error (committed by first baseman Chance Cummings that scored George Sweatt for the first run on a ball hit by Willie Powell) to make it 7-0 Chicago.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Starter Rats Henderson (four innings, seven runs (all unearned) on nine hits with three walks and a strikeout) did not last to see the fifth inning, replaced by Roy Roberts (four innings, three hits, six runs (five earned), six walks, one strikeout).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He would allow four runs to score on the basis of two hits, an error, and three walks.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the sixth inning, an error, a passed ball, and two walks meant the bases were loaded with no one out, and Jelly Gardner doubled to score two runs and close the game at 13–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Willie Powell threw a complete-game shutout while allowing six hits with a walk and a strikeout.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The final game of the Series proved to be the most dramatic, and Chicago would win it all on a walk-off in the ninth despite Bacharach having numerous chances to score in a rematch of Game 7, which had also come down to the final inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach had the first glance at a run in the first inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With two outs, Dick Lundy and Chaney White each lobbed singles to center field, and Joe Lewis walked to load the bases.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, starting pitcher Willie Foster got Chance Cummings to strike out to end the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] The next threat was in the fourth inning for Bacharach, who started with singles by Lewis and Cummings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] However, a force out and two pop-outs led to no runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] They had the next threat in the seventh when they loaded the bases with two singles and a walk, but a flyout by Chaney White to center fielder Jelly Gardner ended that threat.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Chicago never even reached third base until the eighth, when Jim Brown had a walk and advanced to third on two plays for outs, but Foster soon committed an out to end the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Both teams would have their chance to take the lead in the ninth inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bacharach gained a baserunner when Chano García hit a single, although that was followed by a strikeout and a force-out that had Country Brown at first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] He would go for stealing second base, and an error by catcher Brown meant that he was on third base with two out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Oliver Marcell walked to have runners on the corners, but Lundy grounded a ball to shortstop Sanford Jackson, who threw to first baseman George Sweatt to keep the game tied at 0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] In the bottom half of the frame, Jelly Gardner started it with a single to left, and he was advanced to second base on a sacrifice bunt by Dave Malarcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] With Sandy Thompson at bat, he would line a walk-off single to center field that left enough for Gardner to race to home plate and win the Series for Chicago.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1926-colored-world-series] Bill Foster had allowed ten hits but had thrown a complete-game shutout with seven strikeouts and three walks for Chicago; Hubert Lockhart had thrown 8+1⁄3 innings and allowed four hits with one run allowed and a strikeout and a walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The **1927 Colored World Series** was the championship tournament for the 1927 season of Negro league baseball.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It was the fourth overall Series played.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It matched the Chicago American Giants, champions of the Negro National League (1920–1931) and the Bacharach Giants of Atlantic City, New Jersey, champions of the Eastern Colored League.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The Giants won the series five games to three (with one tie).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The two teams had faced a year earlier in the 1926 Colored World Series with the same result.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] This time around, it was Chicago that had to hold back a comeback, since they had won the first four games (all played in Chicago) and needed just one more to clinch the Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] They proceeded to lose three of the next four while tying Game 6, which meant that there could have been a Game 10 if Chicago did not win in Atlantic City.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] They prevailed 11–4 in Game 9 to prevail and win their second straight title.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It was the last Negro World Series played for fifteen years.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] In Game 5, Luther Farrell of the Bacharach Giants pitched a shortened no-hitter, allowing no hits in a 7-inning complete game that was called early due to darkness.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] To get to the World Series, the Giants had to win the NNL Championship Series against the Birmingham Black Barons.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The Giants won Game 1 5-0 and Game 2 10–5 before dropping Game 3 6–5 to close out the Birmingham part of the Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] In Chicago, they won Game 4 6-4 and clinched the pennant with a 6–2 win on September 25.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] For Atlantic City, starter Luther Farrell pitched eight innings while allowing six runs on eight hits while walking one and striking out six and hitting two batters.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie "Bill" Foster allowed two runs on thirteen hits while walking two batters and striking out eight.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Atlantic City would use two pitchers for the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Jesse Hubbard was pulled after pitching four innings and allowing nine runs on eleven hits while striking out one batter.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Hubert Lockhart pitched the remaining four innings while allowing two runs to score on three hits with one walk and three strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie Powell allowed one run to score in nine innings while allowing four hits with three walks and five strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Atlantic City would use three pitchers during the game in another rout loss.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Hubbard was used as the starter for the second straight game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He was replaced after allowing the first two baserunners to advance in the third inning (totaling four hits and four earned runs).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Roy Roberts faced two batters and allowed the runners and one more to score on two hits.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Hubert Lockhart handled the remaining six innings, allowing two runs to score on four hits with one strikeout and on walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Meanwhile, George Harney threw a complete-game shutout, allowing just four hits while walking one batter and striking out eight.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Luther Farrell went eight innings and allowed nine runs to score on eleven hits with six walks and one strikeout, while Webster McDonald pitched nine innings and allowed one run on six hits while walking one and striking out four.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] To the derision of the Chicago teammates, the game was called after seven innings with Atlantic City winning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] According to reports in the *Chicago Defender*, the team started to yell obscene gestures at the box seats where Postmaster Alford and the mayor were sitting.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie Foster pitched six innings and allowed three runs on five hits while walking three and striking out three.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Luther Farrell pitched a shortened no-hitter of seven innings while walking five and striking out three.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago scored in the fourth inning the basis of an error committed by Oliver Marcell that helped Steel Arm Davis get on base; he stole second and third base before Willie Jones committed an error that led Davis to score.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The second run scored in the fifth inning when Larry Brown walked and eventually reached home on an error committed by Cool Turner.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The game ended after ten innings due to darkness.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] This was the first Negro World Series game to have all the runs scored by each team to be composed entirely of home runs.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago starter Willie Powell went six innings and allowed one run on six hits while walking two batters and striking out four.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He was pulled for Eddie Miller, who pitched to one batter in the seventh inning (after Powell had allowed the first two runners to advance) before being pulled for George Harney.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He went 3+2⁄3 innings and allowed two hits, one walk, and two strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] For Atlantic City, Hubert Lockhart pitched ten innings while allowing five hits and one run, walking two and striking out five.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Bacharach left nine runners on base (three times with two runners on) while Chicago left five.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] George Harney allowed eight runs on eleven hits in eight innings of work while walking five and striking out three.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Luther Farrell pitched a complete game while allowing one run on seven hits, six walks, four strikeouts, and two hit batsmen.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Webster McDonald started the game for Chicago, but he would only last four innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] In the fifth inning, he allowed a leadoff triple and two singles that tied the game (in total, he allowed eight hits with one walk and four strikeouts).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie Foster was brought in to relieve him with a batter on first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] An error would later bring the runner home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago went from being up 4–2 to being down 5–4.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Foster would pitch four innings and allow two hits with one run while walking two and striking out one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Jesse Hubbard pitched nine innings for Atlantic City, allowing five runs on six hits with four walks and four strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The game turned in the eighth inning that inspired controversy as the 5–5 tie was broken.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It started with a leadoff double by Clarence Smith, which was followed by a Willie Jones single (followed by a stolen base).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Pinch hitter Ambrose Reid hit a flyball to center fielder Sanford Jackson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The throw by Jackson was a long hard throw that went perfectly to catcher Jim Brown, who had the ball with him to block the plate.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Smith, trying to run home, ran outside the baseline and even ran into the shortstop on the play, but he eventually found a path to home plate and was deemed to have scored.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The argument soon grew heated between the Chicago players and the umpires and fifteen Chicago police officers were brought to the field to restore the peace.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Brown was ejected and three position players switched positions.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago went down in the ninth inning and lost the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago starter Willie Powell pitched one inning and allowed a run to score with two walks and a strikeout before being pulled for Willie Foster.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He threw five innings while allowing three runs to score on eight hits and walking three with one strikeout before Rube Curry was brought in to save the eighth and ninth inning, and he pitched two perfect innings to close an 11–4 win.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] For Atlantic City, starter Hubert Lockhart pitched 1+2⁄3 innings and allowed five runs to score on three hits while walking four before being pulled for Luther Farrell.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He pitched the remaining 6+2⁄3 innings and allowed six runs on 11 hits with one walk and nine strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1930-homestead-grays-season] The **1930 Homestead Grays baseball team** competed as an independent in Negro league baseball during the 1930 baseball season.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1930-homestead-grays-season] The team featured five individuals who were later inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame: manager Cumberland Posey, first baseman Oscar Charleston; catcher Josh Gibson; third baseman Judy Johnson; and pitcher Smokey Joe Williams.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1930-homestead-grays-season] The team's leading pitchers were Smokey Joe Williams (11–5, 2.60 ERA), George Britt (9–3, 2.76 ERA), and Lefty Williams (9–1, 4.18 ERA).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1931-homestead-grays-season] The **1931 Homestead Grays baseball team** competed as an independent in Negro league baseball during the 1931 baseball season.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1931-homestead-grays-season] The team featured seven individuals who were later inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame: manager Cumberland Posey, first baseman Oscar Charleston; catcher Josh Gibson; third baseman Jud Wilson; and pitchers Bill Foster, Smokey Joe Williams, and Satchel Paige.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1931-homestead-grays-season] The team's leading pitchers were Bill Foster (9–2, 2.34 ERA) and Smokey Joe Williams (6–2, 2.41 ERA).
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1936-homestead-grays-season] The **1936 Homestead Grays baseball team** represented the Homestead Grays in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1936 baseball season.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1936-homestead-grays-season] This was the first season with player-manager Vic Harris at the helm.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1936-homestead-grays-season] The team compiled a 25-34–2 record (.426) and finished in seventh place in the NNL.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] In the **1944 Negro World Series**, the Washington Homestead Grays, champions of the Negro National League were matched against the Birmingham Black Barons, champions of the Negro American League, for the second year in a row.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The Grays won the series again, four games to one.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Birmingham went 48-22 while Homestead went 27–12.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] In the opening game, the Grays would get three home runs from three different players - no team had hit more than one in a game since Game 3 of the 1942 Negro World Series, which was also the last time a Gray had hit a home run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] They would use this along with timely hitting to beat the Barons at home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Homestead started the scoring in the first inning with a one-out double by Jerry Benjamin.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] He got to third base after Sam Bankhead and Buck Leonard were walked, and Dave Hoskins would hit into a fielder's choice that scored Hoskins and made it 1–0.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Birmingham matched the score at one in the third inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Felix McLaurin drew a one-out walk and stole second base and went to third after Artie Wilson hit a single.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Ed Steele would then his a single to right field to score the run home.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] However, when Piper Davis hit into a fielders choice to the third baseman, Wilson would be called out at home plate, and Ted Radcliffe would also hit a ball right to the second baseman in Jelly Jackson to get the third out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The tie was broken on the first batter of the fourth inning as Josh Gibson hit a home run to right field to make it 2–1, and Buck Leonard hit a home run to the same porch in the next inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] With the game 3–1, the Barons made one last attempt.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] John Britton lined a single to start the inning and was followed soon by Artie Wilson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] With two out, Steele would hit a ball that was off home plate that was thought to be foul at first.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] However, the umpires ruled that it was a fair ball, thereby making Steele out; the Barons played the rest of the game under protest, to no avail.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] When the Grays came to bat in the eighth, Dave Hoskins hit a leadoff home run to the same porch as the two home run hitters before him to make it 4–1.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Gibson followed with a single, and Walter Cannady had a double to get him to third.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Two outs later, Cool Papa Bell lined a triple to center field that would score Gibson and Cannady to make it 6–1.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Both teams scored in the ninth inning to close the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Bankhead had a single and advanced on a wild pitch and an out to third base, and he scored on a subsequent single by Hoskins.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] A sacrifice hit by Cannady scored Hoskins to close out the Grays end of the bat.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Johnny Markham hit a leadoff single to start the bottom frame, and pinch-runner Collins Jones went to second on a wild pitch before scoring on a one-out Artie Wilson single.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Piper Davis would hit a two-out single to score in Wilson before Ted Radcliffe committed the final out to end the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Starter Roy Welmaker threw nine innings for the Grays and allowed three runs on eleven hits while striking out seven with one walk.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] For the Black Barons, Johnny Markham allowed eight runs on eleven hits while walking four and striking out six.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The Grays started slowly but ran through a late rally to take a 2–0 lead in the Series.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Cool Papa Bell started the game with a leadoff single to center field, but Jerry Benjamin's fielder choice hit meant that Benjamin was on first with one out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] A single by Sam Bankhead and a walk to Buck Leonard loaded the bases for Dave Hoskins.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] He would hit a flyball to center field that Benjamin scored on.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] However, Bankhead was soon thrown out while trying to steal third base and the game was 1–0 after one inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The Black Barons evened the score in the fourth.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] An error by Bankhead at shortstop meant that Piper Davis had gotten to first base with one out, and he made it to second on a passed ball by Josh Gibson.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Two batters later, Lester Lockett hit a two-out double to left field that scored Davis.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] In the seventh, the Grays got the go-ahead run.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Leonard hit a leadoff single and then got to second on a ground out and then stole third base.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Josh Gibson was walked on purpose and then stole second base, and Walter Cannady would score Leonard on a sacrifice fly to center field to make it 2–1 after seven.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The Barons had a serious threat in the latter half of the inning, getting the bases loaded on two singles and a walk, but Felix McLaurin would commit an out to end the inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] They would then add four runs in the ninth inning on the strength of three straight singles (Bankhead, Leonard, Hoskins), an error by the center fielder, a walk, and a two-run single by Edsall Walker with two out.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The Barons had two runners on base with no out and then two out but scored zero runs to end the game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] For the Grays, Walker would allow just one run on five hits while striking out two batters and walking three, and Alfred Saylor allowed six runs on eight hits with four walks and five strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] A hit in the second inning by Ted Radcliffe was all that the Black Barons could muster against Ray Brown, who pitched a one-hitter shutout with three walks and five strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Earl Bumpus allowed nine runs on eleven hits with six walks and strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Homestead got the first run on the board in the second inning, starting with a leadoff single by Dave Hoskins that was followed by a single by Josh Gibson that scored Hoskins.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The fifth inning proved decisive for Homestead, who scored four runs on the strength of two hits (singles by Brown and Cool Papa Bell), a sacrifice bunt, a hit by pitch, and errors by Birmingham's second and third basemen.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The seventh proved no better for the Black Barons, who saw a single by Sam Bankhead eventually turn into a run after two wild pitches were thrown by the pitcher.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The next inning saw them get two outs but it was followed by a single by Jerry Benjamin and a walk to Bankhead before singles by Buck Leonard and Dave Hoskins scored the runners.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] A single by Bell in the final frame scored Cannady (who reached on an error) to end the scoring.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] John Huber threw a complete-game shutout while allowing just three hits with four walks and six strikeouts.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Spoon Carter went five innings for the Grays and would prove to be the only Gray starter in the Series to not throw a complete game.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] He allowed five hits and two runs with a walk and strikeout before being taken out for Edsall Walker.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Walker allowed four runs to score on six hits with four strikeouts for four innings.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Roy Welmaker closed the Series out for the Grays by allowing just two runs to score on eight hits while striking out six batters.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] The Barons had trouble early with pitching that cost them dearly, as starter Alfred Saylor allowed four runs to score on seven hits with three walks before being replaced by Alonzo Boone with one out in the fourth inning.
[src:1944-negro-world-series/1944-negro-world-series] Boone allowed four hits with one walk and three strikeouts.
